  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is 5-HTP and how does it work?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: '5-HTP (5-hydroxytryptophan) is an amino acid that serves as the direct precursor to serotonin — one of the brain\'s most important neurotransmitters. Serotonin regulates mood, sleep, appetite, pain perception, and emotional well-being. 5-HTP is naturally produced in the body from the amino acid tryptophan (found in foods like turkey and dairy) and is then converted to serotonin by the enzyme aromatic amino acid decarboxylase. Supplemental 5-HTP, derived from the African plant Griffonia simplicifolia, bypasses the rate-limiting step of tryptophan-to-5-HTP conversion, providing a more direct pathway to serotonin production. Unlike tryptophan, 5-HTP crosses the blood-brain barrier efficiently, making it a more effective serotonin-boosting supplement.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How much 5-HTP should I take?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Clinical studies have used 5-HTP doses ranging from 50mg to 300mg per day. For mood support, 50-100mg taken 1-3 times daily is common. For sleep improvement, 100-300mg taken 30-60 minutes before bedtime is typical — serotonin is the precursor to melatonin, so increasing serotonin in the evening naturally supports melatonin production. For appetite management, 250-300mg per day has been studied. Most experts recommend starting at 50mg and gradually increasing to assess tolerance. Higher doses exceeding 300mg daily should only be taken under physician supervision.' } },
